Midterm - House Prediction

Jonathan Manurung, June Jaegal

15-12-2023

Introduction

The purpose of this project is to built a better predictive model of home prices for Philadelphia, in order to create better and more accurate version from the Zillow prediction. The resulting model will be used to predict some house prices in Philadelphia, based on their internal characteristic and the Amenities/Public Services nearby using statistical analysis and data-driven insights. We will use experiences from observed data, and test whether they can be used to predict outcomes where and when they are unknown. What makes this modeling exercise challenging is the abundance of potential variables and the need to select the most accurate ones that directly influence the house prices. Additionally, there is a substantial amount of missing data in the provided observed data so data cleaning and filtering need to be performed. The goal of this project is to train a model from observed data with training set, and test whether that model generalizes to properties that have unknown or un-estimated prices. A framework is used in the predictive modeling process. Data wrangling: to compile required data into one dataset and cleaning the outliers. Feature engineering: to create variables used to predict the outcome. Measuring the sum of indicators value within a fixed buffer distance of each home obeserved to see the scale relationship between the variables and home prices; Model estimation and validation: Creating an OLS Regression model that will be used to estimates the home prices as a function of several variables.

Methods

In this prediction, it includes location of park, water surface, landmarks, bridges, universities, SEPTA, local pubs and crime data to predict the housing price. Most of the indicators used here are the common indicators when consumers consider when they purchase for the housing. Our methodology is to create buffers around the points of each indicators to estimate the impacted area around each events. Then, counted the number of events by each indicators around the building. With the dataset created through the process above, we created a trained model using the buildings with given sales_price. Lastly, applied this model to predict the housing price of the buildings with no given sales_price using predict function.

# Filter rows with the specified value in the "toPredict" column
philly_challenge <- filter(philly, toPredict == "CHALLENGE")

philly_filtered <- filter(philly, toPredict == "MODELLING")

philly_filtered <- philly_filtered %>%
  mutate(Age = 2023 - year_built)

philly_challenge <- philly_challenge %>%
  mutate(Age = 2023 - year_built)

reg1<-lm(sale_price ~ ., data = 
           st_drop_geometry(philly_filtered)%>%
           dplyr::select(sale_price,park.Buffer, crime.Buffer, water.Buffer,transit.Buffer, pub.Buffer, university.Buffer, landmark.Buffer, bridge.Buffer, Age, number_stories, total_area))
set.seed(123)

inTrain <- createDataPartition(
  y = paste(philly_filtered$park.Buffer, philly_filtered$crime.Buffer, philly_filtered$water.Buffer, philly_filtered$transit.Buffer, philly_filtered$pub.Buffer, philly_filtered$university.Buffer, philly_filtered$landmark.Buffer, philly_filtered$bridge.Buffer, philly_filtered$Age, philly_filtered$number_stories, philly_filtered$total_area), 
  p = 0.60, list = FALSE
)

philly_filtered.training <- philly_filtered[inTrain, ]
philly_filtered.test <- philly_filtered[-inTrain, ]

reg.training <- lm(
  sale_price ~ .,
  data = as.data.frame(philly_filtered.training) %>%
    dplyr::select(sale_price, park.Buffer, crime.Buffer, water.Buffer, transit.Buffer, pub.Buffer, university.Buffer, landmark.Buffer, bridge.Buffer, Age, number_stories, total_area)
)

Table of Goodness of fit (Test Set)

philly_filtered.test <-
  philly_filtered.test %>%
  mutate(Regression = "Baseline Regression",
         sale_price.Predict = predict(reg.training, philly_filtered.test),
         sale_price.Error = sale_price.Predict - sale_price,
         sale_price.AbsError = abs(sale_price.Predict - sale_price),
         sale_price.APE = (abs(sale_price.Predict - sale_price)) / sale_price.Predict)%>%
  filter(sale_price < 5000000) 
mae_test <- mean(philly_filtered.test$sale_price.AbsError, na.rm = T)
mae_std_dev <- sd(philly_filtered.test$sale_price.AbsError, na.rm = T)
mape_test <- mean(philly_filtered.test$sale_price.APE, na.rm = T)
mape_std_dev <- sd(philly_filtered.test$sale_price.APE, na.rm = T)

# Create a data frame with the results
results <- data.frame(
  Metric = c("Mean Absolute Error (MAE)","Standard Deviation Absolute Error (MAPE)", "Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE)", "Standard Deviation Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE)"),
  Value = c(mae_test,mae_std_dev, mape_test, mape_std_dev)
)

# Display the table
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)

kable(results, format = "html", col.names = c("Metric", "Value"), align = "c") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

Measures of error are attributed to each sale, some basic summary statistics describe goodness of fit. First, Mean Absolute Error (MAE) is calculated. The error is not trivial given the mean Sale_Price for our test data (Philly.test) is $101,173.87. Next, Mean Absolute Percent Error is calculated by taking the mean SalePrice.APE. MAPE value is about 40% which can be still considered as reasonable forecasting.

Residual Map

coords <- st_coordinates(philly_filtered) 

neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords, 5))

spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")

philly_filtered$lagPrice <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, philly_filtered$sale_price)
coords.test <-  st_coordinates(philly_filtered.test) 

neighborList.test <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords.test, 5))

spatialWeights.test <- nb2listw(neighborList.test, style="W")

philly_filtered.test %>%
  mutate(lagPriceError = lag.listw(spatialWeights.test, sale_price.Error)) %>%
  ggplot()+
  geom_point(aes(x =lagPriceError, y =sale_price.Error))

philly_filtered.test$residuals <- philly_filtered.test$sale_price - philly_filtered.test$sale_price.Predict
res <- st_join(neighborhood, philly_filtered.test, by = "name")

resmap <- res %>% 
  group_by(name.x)

resmap <- resmap %>% 
  summarize(Mean_Residual = mean(residuals))

quantiles <- quantile(resmap$Mean_Residual, probs = seq(0, 1, by = 0.2), na.rm = TRUE)

quantile_labels <- labels <- sprintf("%0.1f", quantiles)

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = resmap, aes(fill = Mean_Residual)) +
  scale_fill_distiller(breaks = quantiles, labels = quantile_labels, palette = "RdYlBu", direction = -1) +
  labs(title = "Residual Map",
       fill = "Residual") +
  theme_minimal()

The map is showing the residual between actual sale price and predicted sale price by neighborhood. The neighborhood in bottom left of Philadelphia shows highest residual. It means that there is the most difference between predicted and observed housing price in dollars.

Morans I

moranTest <- moran.mc(philly_filtered.test$sale_price.Error, 
                      spatialWeights.test, nsim = 999)

ggplot(as.data.frame(moranTest$res[c(1:999)]), aes(moranTest$res[c(1:999)])) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = moranTest$statistic), colour = "#FA7800",size=1) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(title="Observed and permuted Moran's I",
       subtitle= "Observed Moran's I in orange",
       x="Moran's I",
       y="Count") +
  plotTheme()

Morans I observed value is about 0.3. First, as the value is positive value, it has positive spatial autocorrelation. It explains that when the buildings are located in similar areas, their predicted housing prices are also similar. However, the grey line are clustered near 0.0. It means that permuted values are not showing much spatial autocorrelation between buildings.

MAPE by Neighborhood

st_drop_geometry(bothRegressions) %>%
  group_by(Regression, name) %>%
  summarize(mean.MAPE = mean(sale_price.APE, na.rm = T)) %>%

  left_join(neighborhood) %>%
    st_sf() %>%
    ggplot() +

The visualization shows that the higher MAPE region are different across baseline regression and neighborhood effects. For baseline regression, the highest MAPE locates at bottom left of Philadelphia. However, for neighborhood effects, MAPE value is fairly consistent across Philadelphia.

  summarize(mean.MAPE = scales::percent(mean(sale_price.APE, na.rm = T))) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  spread(incomeContext, mean.MAPE) %>%
  kable(caption = "Test set MAPE by neighborhood income context")
Test set MAPE by neighborhood income context
Regression High Income Low Income
Baseline Regression 47% 34%
Neighborhood Effects 84% 44%

As shown above, we split the census by race and income. There is a close gap in difference in goodness of fit across the races, but the gap is closer for the Baseline Regression model. The same trend is evident for income, with the Neighborhood Effect exhibiting higher error rate differences across income contexts. It is now clear how the inclusion of neighborhood effects makes the model more generalizable.

Discussion - Accuracy

Accuracy of prediction using our own model cannot be said as accurate model. First of all, the value of MAE is pretty huge. It means that there are large difference between observed and predicted value. It will lead to the result of the predicted housing price of the test set. In addition, RMSE value is high compared to the range of the housing price. However, from the linear line from the scatterplot of observed and predicted housing price, we can see that it has the correct trend of housing price.

Discussion - Generalizability

Generalizability is to figure out whether the spatial trend of the predicted housing price is well predicted. R-squared value is at 45%, so it proved that the model included decent degree of spatial trend, but it is hard to say that the model has good generalizability. Also, standard deviation of MAE is relatively high compared to the range of housing price. These statistical indicators shows that generalizability of the model is not high enough to make the predicted housing price as credible.

Conclusion & Recommendation

In conclusion, our model to predict the housing price was not good enough to help consumers who are willing to buy a house. Hence, we do not recommend our model to Zillow. Although they were merely helpful in both accuracy and generalizability, it is not good enough to be a credible model.
